You&#39;ve an issue on your if statement. 
You&#39;re using a single `=` that is used for variable assignment. For that reason is always setting the font family to &quot;OpenDyslexic&quot;. 
I suggest you to use the strict equality comparison: `===`

The code without errors should be:

    function myFunction() {
        var x = document.getElementById(&quot;body&quot;)
        if (x.style.fontFamily === &quot;OpenDyslexic&quot;) {
            x.style.fontFamily = &quot;OpenDyslexic&quot;;
        } else {
            x.style.fontFamily = &quot;Noto&quot;;
        } }

Two issues in your code:

1. You are using assignment operator (`=`) where you should use the comparison operator (`==` or `===`), hence the condition always evaluates to `true`.

2. You are setting the same value for the property if the condition is `true` which is logically incorrect.

